On the first day of August, I reported that Pioneer Square mystery bookstore Seattle Mystery Bookshop was for sale. Last night, a number of Seattle-area book journalists received an email from Seattle Mystery Bookshop owner J.B. Dickey. &ldquo;We&rsquo;ve received no firm offers for the shop,&rdquo; Dickey says, &ldquo;so it feels as if it is time to start winding things down.&rdquo;
&ldquo;Most likely the end of the month will be it,&rdquo; Dickey explains.

The Hugo House just made their slate of fall classes available to non-members. There&rsquo;s a lot of great stuff there, but here are a couple of classes to keep in mind from people who have published here at the Seattle Review of Books.
 Anca Szilágyi is teaching two classes: a one-day class titled &ldquo;Wall-to-Wall Writing Prompts,&rdquo; and a full 6-session fiction writing class called &ldquo;Fiction I.&rdquo;
 Similarly, poetry phenom Jamaica Baldwin is teaching &ldquo;Poetry I,&rdquo; a six-class course offering the basics of poetry writing.

![](/webhook-uploads/1486620166498/sexcastle.jpg)
Early in Sexcastle, a random goon threatens Shane Sexcastle by asking, &ldquo;You ever hear the phrase &lsquo;You brought a knife to a gun fight?&rsquo;&rdquo;
Sexcastle responds, &ldquo;This is worse than that. You brought a you to a me fight.&rdquo;
Sexcastle was first published almost two years ago, but it had escaped my attention until the good folks at Phoenix Comics turned me on to it last night. I was interested in an upcoming comic called Rock Candy Mountain about a hobo’s epic journey by a cartoonist named Kyle Starks, and they happened to have his first book in stock.

This is a neat idea: Alexander Chee is taking over the Hugo House&rsquo;s Instagram feed this week to provide teasers of the story he&rsquo;ll be reading at the House&rsquo;s Literary Series event this Friday.
 Happy Halloween! This has to be the best literary Halloween tweet of the year:
  I just passed a young woman wearing a sombrero, would be so dope if her costume was &quot;lionel shriver&quot;

Have you read Sarah Galvin&rsquo;s great review of Michelle Tea&rsquo;s new memoir/novel Black Wave yet? You should! It&rsquo;s a wonderful celebration of Tea&rsquo;s impact on young readers that also includes the words &ldquo;sex millionaire.&rdquo;
Tea herself notified us last night, however, that the review needs one correction:
