Yesterday, I told you that In Other Words, the feminist bookstore featured in the TV show Portlandia under the fictional name Women &amp; Women First, had put a &ldquo;Fuck Portlandia&rdquo; sign in its window, and when the Willamette Week reached out for comment, bookstore staff told the Week to &ldquo;go fuck themselves.&rdquo;
Now, In Other Words has written a post explaining the sign. Also titled &ldquo;Fuck Portlandia,&rdquo; the post makes a great case for why In Other Words doesn&rsquo;t want to play by the show&rsquo;s rules anymore:

This, which we found on poet Kelli Russell Agodon&rsquo;s Twitter feed, is a terrific idea: poet.tips recommends poets to you, in the by-now-ubiquitous internet recommendation format of &ldquo;If you like X, then you&rsquo;ll like Y.&rdquo; The engine stretches from classics&hellip;
 Edna St. Vincent Millay T.S. Eliot Denise Levertov  &hellip;to contemporary greats&hellip;
 Patricia Lockwood Dorothea Lasky Alice Notley Eileen Myles  &hellip;to local favorites:
 Kelli Russell Agodon Sherman Alexie Karen Finneyfrock Maged Zaher  Recommendation engines are not the be-all end-all of discovery, of course, but they can send you on some interesting tangents.

I first encountered this tweet while I was reading Johanna Sinisalo&rsquo;s wonderful The Core of the Sun:
Has anyone ever opened a novel and said &quot;Oh good, a long passage in italics&quot;
&mdash; Elisa Gabbert (@egabbert) January 1, 2016 And while I guess I&rsquo;ve never opened up a novel and been excited about the presence of italics, I&rsquo;ve certainly never been disappointed to see italics, either. The Core of the Sun features quite a few passages in italics — the book is made up of a collage of letters and dictionary entries and other odds and ends — and it works really well; the italics signify difference in a visual shorthand that&rsquo;s not quite as jarring as, say, switching to a different font.

This week&rsquo;s sponsor is Robert James Russell, and we&rsquo;re featuring a full chapter from his upcoming western, Mesilla, a release from Seattle&rsquo;s own Dock Street Press. Our thanks to him for the support.
Our favorite quote about this book is from Peter Geye: &ldquo;If Albert Camus had written westerns, they might have sounded something like Robert James Russell&rsquo;s Mesilla.&rdquo; - Peter Geye&rdquo;
